column49: I did not update because I am unsure as to whether I will be using Scholastic anymore. Earlier in the year, I was informed that if I place an order for my classroom and mail it from school, I am responsible for paying the shipping costs, but if a parent orders and has it sent to the student's home, there is no shipping fee. I don't understand this. Why should I have to pay shipping? I would think it would be most cost effective for you to eat the costs of shipping and only have to send a box to one place (the school) as opposed to several? I would love to hear the thinking on this. I called and complained about this at the beginning of the year and was told that there would be follow up but have heard nothing.

column49: I am not happy that I had one of my student's order processed and auto shipped to the school. I had to make 3 phone calls to Scholastic about this.  I did not get all of the rewards I was supposed to get since my orders were not processed together and I had to request a link to the Dollar books since the remaining orders for me to process only equaled $71. After being frustrated with this whole process, I submitted my class order but did not order anything.  I should not have to call to place my Dollar books order because you did something without my permission.  The purpose of online ordering is to make things quick and efficient.  I am considering not doing Scholastic book orders next year.  The books are very expensive now and you are making it difficult for teachers to use and get books for their students.

column49: I actually said to my husband, as I was filling out the order, that I love this site. My son takes the paper flyers home and we have a great time going through the paper flyers - picking out books, discussing fun new books to consider, etc. Then we order online - as we often like books from multiple flyers and the site makes it SO easy to find the books across the flyers and make a single order. I love that it makes recommendations of similar books, that you can sort by grade, search by author, etc. It's so user-friendly and makes it so fun to explore books!

column49: As a teacher I am very disappointed to see that not once this year were $1 books available for purchase.  Teachers spend enough money throughout the school year on their students and classrooms. The one thing we look forward to is value from Scholastic. It cost me double this year to buy summer books for my students.  I realize prices are up but it's the teachers who push out the marketing and help you generate revenue through our classrooms. The least you can do is provide $1 books to teachers either at Christmas time or in June.  It makes me not want to even provide flyers and opportunities to my class next year to order books from Scholastic.

column41: Submit an order to my child’s teacher
column49: I can almost always find a book or two for my kids so I appreciate the flyers that they look through and can tell me what they like. If I may, I'd like to share that I wish you would include more books that reflect the Christian faith. For example, at Easter time there weren't any that were even remotely related to Jesus and I ended up not purchasing any at that time. I know you probably have to be careful what books you put out, but when I see books like Horrorland, Mary will I die, Possess me, etc. I wonder why there can't be a couple books on popular bible stories or even bible principles such as the fruit of the spirit- love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self control. I hope you'll consider carrying these kinds of books. I would be more likely to share about the scholastic book club with my friends if that were the case. Thank you for your consideration.
